Air China, China Citic: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-01T10:06:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-01/air-china-bank-of-china-china-citic-ping-an-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
(Corrects ticker and stock price for BOC  Hong Kong  in story
that originally ran on March 31.)  The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.3 percent to 23,527.52. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, rose 1.2 percent to 13,315.84.  Air China Ltd. (601111)  (753 HK), China Eastern Airlines Corp. (670
HK): The airlines reduced capacity on flights to  Japan  as
concerns about radiation leaking from a crippled nuclear-power
plant hammers travel. Air China, the nation’s largest
international carrier, dropped 2.2 percent to HK$7.20. China
Eastern Airlines slid 0.7 percent to HK$2.99.  BOC Hong Kong (Holdings) Ltd. (2388 HK): The city’s sole
clearing bank for yuan banking services cut its interest rate
for yuan deposits in Hong Kong after money held in the accounts
rose to a record in February. The stock gained 1.2 percent to
HK$25.35.  Beijing Enterprises Holdings Ltd. (392)  (392 HK): The gas
distributor said full-year net income rose 10 percent to HK$2.64
billion ($403 million). The stock advanced 0.9 percent to
HK$44.40.  China Citic Bank Corp. (998 HK): The banking unit of the
nation’s largest investment firm said full-year net income rose
to 21.5 billion yuan from 14.3 billion yuan in 2009. The average
estimate of 14 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg was 20.9 billion
yuan. Separately, the company said Chairman Kong Dan resigned
and quit as a non-executive director, effective upon the
appointment of his replacement. The stock advanced 2 percent to
HK$5.66.  China Merchants Bank Co. (3968 HK): The lender said profit
rose 41 percent in 2010 to 25.8 billion yuan as lending margins
widened and income grew from loans and fee-based services. The
stock increased 1.2 percent to HK$21.55.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (1398)  Ltd. (1398 HK): The
biggest lender in China by market value sold $260 million of
three-year notes due April 2014, according to a person familiar
with the matter. The stock rose 1.3 percent to HK$6.46.  Melco International Development Ltd. (200)  (200 HK): The company
posted a full-year net loss of HK$209.5 million, compared with
HK$1.45 billion net loss a year earlier. The stock declined 0.8
percent to HK$5.30.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. (2318 HK): China’s second-
largest insurer will boost fixed-income investments this year to
tap rising yields and may “slightly” increase equities in the
portfolio as it turns more optimistic on stocks, President Alex
Ren said. The stock climbed 2.2 percent to HK$78.85.  Television Broadcasts Ltd. (511)  (511 HK). The free-to-air
broadcaster’s substantial shareholder, Shaw Brothers (Hong Kong)
Ltd., completed disposal of its stake in the Hong Kong
broadcaster, the company said in a statement to the city’s stock
exchange. Hong Kong’s Broadcasting Authority approved the
shareholding changes, the statement said. The shares gained 1.3
percent to HK$45.70.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Tokyo  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 